1
00:00:02,242 --> 00:00:12,916
As we're coming toward the close of the retreat, I thought it would be fitting to look at the last of the Buddha's teachings, the Mahaparinibbana Sutta, known as the Buddha's Last Days.

2
00:00:14,237 --> 00:00:18,623
Nibbana, as you know, describes the state experienced by those who are enlightened.

3
00:00:19,583 --> 00:00:26,713
The fires of passion extinguish themselves in Nibbana, and so extinguishing is one translation for Nibbana.

4
00:00:27,824 --> 00:00:47,789
If this seems like a bleak goal for the spiritual life, we have Bhikkhu Thanissaro's assurance that in the Buddha's time it was believed that an extinguished fire went into a state of potential, liberated from its location to suffuse the whole universe with its energy.

5
00:00:49,593 --> 00:00:59,848
This ties in with alternative translations for Nibbāna such as unbinding, liberation, freedom, the deathless, the unborn.

6
00:01:01,210 --> 00:01:05,737
And of course we have positive descriptions of Nibbāna as perfect happiness and contentment.

7
00:01:08,302 --> 00:01:15,852
The Buddha entered the state of Nibbāna when he fully understood the Four Noble Truths as he sat under the Bodhi tree in Bodh Gaya.

8
00:01:17,115 --> 00:01:28,581
He then taught others how to come to the same understanding for over four decades until, aged 80, his body dies and he enters the state known as Parinibbana.

9
00:01:30,144 --> 00:01:34,956
This term refers to Nibbana after the dissolution of the five aggregates.

10
00:01:37,129 --> 00:01:45,457
Unenlightened beings like us cling to these aggregates of body and mind in the mistaken belief that these constitute our essential being.

11
00:01:47,219 --> 00:01:56,147
The Buddha ceased clinging at Bodhgaya, but his transcendent knowledge and understanding could still manifest within the world through these aggregates.

12
00:01:57,289 --> 00:02:03,254
At the moment of death, his transcendence became completely non-manifest, untraceable.

13
00:02:05,682 --> 00:02:10,288
The Buddha does not answer questions of the form, does the Buddha exist after death?

14
00:02:11,610 --> 00:02:18,979
The state of the Buddha is beyond measure, he says, so it is meaningless to speak of this in terms of existence or non-existence.

15
00:02:20,622 --> 00:02:32,937
The Parinibbana Sutta does not try to unpick this conundrum, nor does it attempt any description of Nibbana or Parinibbana, but simply reports the facts of the Buddha's last days.

16
00:02:35,568 --> 00:02:42,777
Most commentators agree that the Sutta has been embroidered by devotees who wished to remember the Buddha in exalted terms.

17
00:02:43,860 --> 00:02:50,308
For example, he is said to have transported himself over the river Ganges along with all his order of monks.

18
00:02:51,790 --> 00:02:56,918
He later caused an earthquake by revoking his will to live and another as he died.

19
00:02:57,961 --> 00:03:07,572
Muddy waters miraculously cleared to let him drink, his skin glowed brighter than gold, and flowers bloomed out of season to honour him on his deathbed.

20
00:03:09,054 --> 00:03:21,588
There are seemingly pointless stories, for example, of people locking their chariot wheels as they vie to have him attend their house for a meal, almost as the paparazzi pursue modern-day celebrities.

21
00:03:23,358 --> 00:03:34,418
As against this, there are many credible and inspiring descriptions of his last days, which we can use as a teaching on closure, how we might hope to end our own lives.

22
00:03:35,419 --> 00:03:45,417
And of course, we can practice on a smaller scale, using this as a model of how to take our leave from any activity, even from this retreat, for example.

23
00:03:47,707 --> 00:03:51,491
At the start of the Sutta, there is no talk of his impending death.

24
00:03:52,572 --> 00:03:58,818
It seems he is just doing what he had spent the past decades doing, going from place to place, teaching the Dhamma.

25
00:04:00,258 --> 00:04:05,462
Despite his frail old body, he is almost constantly on the road during these last days.

26
00:04:06,724 --> 00:04:17,613
He starts out in Vulture's Peak and we are told of 17 stopping points before he reaches his final resting place at a grove of sal trees at Kushinara.

27
00:04:19,230 --> 00:04:26,161
I was fortunate enough to have visited Vultures Peak and the Salgrove when on pilgrimage with Bhante and others in 2006.

28
00:04:27,865 --> 00:04:30,728
The distance between them is almost 200 miles.

29
00:04:32,151 --> 00:04:34,995
Even in the comfort of a saloon car it was a long journey.

30
00:04:36,017 --> 00:04:46,233
Imagine the energy and resolve involved in doing that on foot as an 80-year-old in chronic pain and with a body that was just about holding together.

31
00:04:47,733 --> 00:04:51,480
To follow the Buddha's example is not just to sit on our cushions.

32
00:04:52,100 --> 00:04:59,173
We must also give ourselves wholeheartedly to whatever activities we choose to do in the service of others.

33
00:05:01,798 --> 00:05:08,711
Much of the main drama of the Sutta happens in Vasali, the region where the Buddha had found his first meditation teacher.

34
00:05:09,687 --> 00:05:14,475
He also returned here after enlightenment to teach and establish monastic settlements.

35
00:05:15,576 --> 00:05:20,165
It is in Vasali that the business of the Buddha's death starts to loom large.

36
00:05:21,427 --> 00:05:23,471
He makes his final rains retreat here.

37
00:05:24,632 --> 00:05:30,041
During the retreat he becomes very ill and realizes he's in danger of death.

38
00:05:30,021 --> 00:05:36,492
He considers it would be unfitting to die in this way without having taken proper leave of his disciples.

39
00:05:37,535 --> 00:05:45,870
And so we are told he made a tremendous effort to summon the will to live and thereby overcame his sickness.

40
00:05:48,634 --> 00:05:54,023
This is a good illustration of the Buddha's care for individuals and not just for humanity at large.

41
00:05:55,444 --> 00:05:58,129
It would have been easy to throw in the towel.

42
00:05:58,971 --> 00:06:04,439
He had accomplished his mission to achieve enlightenment and teach others how to follow in his footsteps.

43
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:07,863
He had achieved all his broader goals.

44
00:06:08,985 --> 00:06:13,932
But he was also concerned for the particular, for Ananda and his companions.

45
00:06:14,790 --> 00:06:22,413
He didn't want to have them finding out news of his death while they were on retreat themselves and all the confusion that would cause.

46
00:06:24,279 --> 00:06:29,154
He wanted to die in a way that would minimize trouble for those he was leaving behind.

47
00:06:30,838 --> 00:06:49,370
The great effort the Buddha made to overcome this illness is also a sober reminder to get our own affairs in order so that our death will cause minimal disturbance to others, making a will, tackling thorny issues like end-of-life care and deciding how much intervention we want.

48
00:06:50,735 --> 00:07:02,230
These aren't easy matters to address, but any headway we can make is our best attempt to follow the Buddha's example to care for others up to and beyond the point of our death.

49
00:07:05,872 --> 00:07:09,139
Happily the Buddha was able to overcome his illness.

50
00:07:10,161 --> 00:07:15,512
Afterwards Ananda tells the Buddha how distressed he had been to see the Buddha so near death.

51
00:07:16,653 --> 00:07:25,973
The only thought that consoled him he said was that he was sure the Buddha would not die without making a statement about who should lead the monks after his death.

52
00:07:27,437 --> 00:07:32,783
The Buddha seems surprised by this, asking, What does the order expect of me?

53
00:07:32,822 --> 00:07:38,569
For himself, he says, he doesn't think of the order in terms of needing a leader.

54
00:07:39,509 --> 00:07:53,985
Instead, he advises that you should live like islands unto yourselves, be in your own refuge, with no one else as your refuge, with the Dharma as your refuge and no other refuge.

55
00:07:56,259 --> 00:08:01,026
Thus, he doesn't try to extend his influence over the Order beyond his own lifetime.

56
00:08:02,449 --> 00:08:05,814
He fully accepted the limitations of his human form.

57
00:08:07,576 --> 00:08:15,086
The Order might be expecting him to look into the future and work out what would be best, but he has no such God-like view of himself.

58
00:08:16,589 --> 00:08:21,677
Having done his job of teaching and leading, he's now going to let go completely.

59
00:08:23,226 --> 00:08:33,264
He leaves no clear authority structure and instead asks that each person take responsibility for their own liberation, using the Dhamma as their guide.

60
00:08:35,508 --> 00:08:41,118
This empowers everyone to get on with the job themselves and guards against the corrupting effect of power.

61
00:08:42,541 --> 00:08:46,246
A very wise and trusting approach to the future of the Dhamma.

62
00:08:47,543 --> 00:08:53,654
He is leaving it up to all of us to carry on his life's work, which is an inspiring thought.

63
00:08:55,918 --> 00:09:10,547
As if to stress the limitations of his earthly form and drive home that people need to take full responsibility for their own liberation and not look on him as some form of God, the Buddha describes his body as old and worn out.

64
00:09:11,707 --> 00:09:23,346
Just as an old cart is made to go by being held together with straps, so the Tathagatha's body is kept going by being strapped up.

65
00:09:23,366 --> 00:09:29,937
We might think that the enlightened state would somehow let the Buddha float above problems like the aches and pains of old age.

66
00:09:31,333 --> 00:09:50,169
Although he didn't identify himself with these limitations, he was intimately aware of them and tells Ananda that the only time his body feels comfortable is when he withdraws his attention from mundane matters to enter a state of deep concentration, devoid of perceptions.

67
00:09:53,423 --> 00:09:55,988
There are a couple of points worth reflecting on here.

68
00:09:56,950 --> 00:10:05,666
Firstly, that the Buddha was normally attending to mundane matters and has to deliberately withdraw attention in order to give his body some comfort.

69
00:10:07,428 --> 00:10:12,658
Enlightenment obviously doesn't mean living in a cloud of bliss, disconnected from the world.

70
00:10:12,698 --> 00:10:17,187
The freedom of Nibbāna can be found within the mundane.

71
00:10:19,072 --> 00:10:26,789
Sometimes we confuse Nibbana or the path of Nibbana with very exalted states we might touch upon in meditation.

72
00:10:28,192 --> 00:10:38,095
While these give us wonderful glimpses of the potential for our human mind, we can overvalue them and then reject ordinary life as worthless by comparison.

73
00:10:39,104 --> 00:11:02,073
It helps us counter this natural preference for meditative bliss when we reflect that the enlightened mind of the Buddha was normally engaged with the mundane details of life, seeing whatever was in front of his eyes, tasting his food, noticing memories and perceptions registering in consciousness, feeling the pain of his 80-year-old body.

74
00:11:04,432 --> 00:11:07,518
Enlightenment does not protect the Buddha from pain.

75
00:11:07,557 --> 00:11:16,453
The only difference between his experience of pain and ours is that he would not have added to the problem with any emotional turmoil.

76
00:11:17,115 --> 00:11:23,285
He wouldn't have got irritable or exasperated or felt hard done by or anything like that.

77
00:11:23,636 --> 00:11:28,524
He could continually find the escape from suffering within the experience of an aching body.

78
00:11:29,705 --> 00:11:36,875
Thus he could accept the pain, discomfort, indignity and other limitations of ageing with serene equanimity.

79
00:11:40,099 --> 00:11:42,802
Pain and sickness can make us feel very vulnerable.

80
00:11:44,104 --> 00:11:49,932
We lose that all-important sense of being in control of our bodies, directing the show.

81
00:11:51,802 --> 00:12:08,865
The path to enlightenment involves the very humbling lesson that we cannot escape the horrors of illness except by getting close to that sense of horror, watching it dissolve moment after moment in the light of awareness in the midst of our illness.

82
00:12:10,432 --> 00:12:24,863
we can encourage ourselves with the thought that the Buddha experienced exactly this kind of challenge and somehow found peace within it, as well as the determination to continue on his long and arduous last journey.

83
00:12:27,711 --> 00:12:36,027
The next stop on that journey is at the Kapala shrine where he and Ananda go after their alms round on the following day.

84
00:12:36,086 --> 00:12:45,484
The Buddha remarks on the beauty of the shrine and names the many other shrines he finds delightful in this region of Vasali.

85
00:12:47,269 --> 00:12:58,744
Although his body is old and worn out, and he's only just recovered from an illness that brought him close to death, he now declares that it would be within his power to live for a full century.

86
00:13:00,625 --> 00:13:06,033
We're told he makes this declaration several times at different shrines around Vasali.

87
00:13:07,215 --> 00:13:14,003
In one breath, he remarks on the beauty of the place, and in the next, declares that he could live out a full century.

88
00:13:15,147 --> 00:13:22,261
Each time, we are told, the Buddha was giving Ananda a hint to request that he live for another 20 years.

89
00:13:23,784 --> 00:13:29,135
Had Ananda taken the hint, the Buddha would then have assented to his friend's request.

90
00:13:32,081 --> 00:13:34,606
There are a couple of points here worth reflecting on.

91
00:13:36,139 --> 00:13:40,124
One is to note the importance that mudita plays in the Buddha's life.

92
00:13:41,525 --> 00:13:48,373
Mudita is one of the four Brahmavihara, so it's hardly surprising to find him practicing this in his last days.

93
00:13:49,715 --> 00:13:53,958
And yet, it is worth reflecting on the implications of this more deeply.

94
00:13:56,182 --> 00:14:01,067
We can take it that the Buddha didn't need earthly beauty to be perfectly happy.

95
00:14:01,908 --> 00:14:06,614
He had transcended suffering and would have been quite equanimous in a slimy pit.

96
00:14:07,875 --> 00:14:16,586
Why then does he take the trouble to notice and admire what he considered beautiful, take delight in it and comment so frequently on it?

97
00:14:17,267 --> 00:14:19,129
Mudita energizes us.

98
00:14:20,211 --> 00:14:25,738
Think of how your heart lifts when you see a beautiful vista, how vibrant you suddenly feel.

99
00:14:26,274 --> 00:14:27,517
It's the same for the Buddha.

100
00:14:28,798 --> 00:14:36,850
Although his default position is equanimity, he needs supportive conditions to feel joy and let that invigorate his body and mind.

101
00:14:38,030 --> 00:14:41,296
He is perhaps more human than we let ourselves believe.

102
00:14:42,758 --> 00:14:49,126
At 80 years of age and following on a serious illness, his life energy is running low.

103
00:14:51,200 --> 00:15:01,572
Moved by the beauty of the shrines at Vasali, Mudita moves him to declare that he could, if necessary, maintain the will to live a further 20 years.

104
00:15:04,397 --> 00:15:19,856
If Mudita could spur the Buddha's will to live, it can surely generate very beneficial energies within us, helping us bear with difficulties, lifting our hearts for some arduous task, inspiring us to better things.

105
00:15:21,135 --> 00:15:31,292
Often we feel so overburdened by our troubles that we don't spend any time appreciating nature, architecture, music or any kind of art.

106
00:15:32,553 --> 00:15:38,364
The Parinibbana Sutta encourages us to connect with the delightful aspects of the world.

107
00:15:39,345 --> 00:15:41,067
Let them lift our hearts.

108
00:15:43,528 --> 00:15:57,341
Tomorrow afternoon, after you've been liberated from the rigours of the retreat, spend some time really looking at things, flowers, trees, the view, or any of the statuary here in Satipanya.

109
00:15:58,682 --> 00:16:03,668
You never know how this might repay you when you're trying to overcome a deathly illness.

110
00:16:05,730 --> 00:16:11,916
When I was recovering from laryngectomy, anxiety was like a transistor radio blaring in my ear.

111
00:16:13,110 --> 00:16:17,677
But when I looked at a flower, the radio switched itself off momentarily.

112
00:16:19,178 --> 00:16:27,589
And as I gazed out my window at a tree, it was as if all those jarring notes were being absorbed within its branches and leaves.

113
00:16:29,270 --> 00:16:42,628
Although I didn't think of this in terms of survival and rekindling the will to live, in retrospect, I can see that these moments of relative ease possibly gave my body the rest it needed to recover.

114
00:16:46,404 --> 00:16:50,049
Another point to acknowledge is the value of our human relationships.

115
00:16:51,552 --> 00:16:57,861
If a good friend asks us to do something, this can spur us well beyond what we would otherwise be prepared to do.

116
00:16:59,585 --> 00:17:10,000
The Buddha's need for Ananda to request that he live on to his potential lifespan of a hundred years gives us further evidence that transcendence did not make him all-powerful.

117
00:17:11,144 --> 00:17:18,070
Supportive conditions, such as the request of a friend, were also needed to maintain his life energy.

118
00:17:20,373 --> 00:17:26,778
If the Buddha could need a friend to spur his resolve, how much more do we need good friends to spur us on?

119
00:17:28,800 --> 00:17:35,387
Any time and effort we spend on developing friendships within our Sangha is time spent on our path to freedom.

120
00:17:36,769 --> 00:17:40,492
We want to be connected to people who will bring out the best in us

121
00:17:43,779 --> 00:17:50,449
It's also worth noting the wisdom in the Buddha's leaving it up to Ananda to make the request that he live a further 20 years.

122
00:17:52,191 --> 00:17:57,557
My grandfather used to say, if a thing is worth having, it's worth asking for.

123
00:18:00,521 --> 00:18:03,727
Doubtless, there would have been a value in the Buddha living for longer.

124
00:18:04,748 --> 00:18:07,771
He would have helped hundreds, possibly thousands of people.

125
00:18:09,253 --> 00:18:10,715
But he had to die sometime.

126
00:18:11,724 --> 00:18:15,190
there was always going to be some limit on the good he could do on earth.

127
00:18:17,713 --> 00:18:20,336
He wasn't one to take on hardship to no avail.

128
00:18:20,377 --> 00:18:32,535
When he first considered teaching, he decided against it, believing that people wouldn't understand him and so he would only be wearing himself out for no good reason, exasperating himself.

129
00:18:34,076 --> 00:18:40,787
Although an enlightened being does not suffer, neither do they choose hardship unless there is a good reason.

130
00:18:43,500 --> 00:18:50,910
Likewise, we can be judicious in what we offer to others, taking our needs and limitations into account.

131
00:18:53,133 --> 00:18:57,999
It is generous to do many acts of kindness quietly without waiting to be asked.

132
00:18:59,681 --> 00:19:06,469
But when the task is arduous, it's best to follow the Buddha's lead and just hint that we could do this.

133
00:19:08,352 --> 00:19:11,095
Generosity needs to be balanced by wisdom.

134
00:19:12,323 --> 00:19:22,076
Otherwise, we could expend much of our life energy doing work that others aren't ready to support or value, and which might therefore be a waste of effort.

135
00:19:25,058 --> 00:19:31,567
Back to the Sutta now, where Ananda fails to take the Buddha's hint and makes no request that the Buddha live to his full century.

136
00:19:32,808 --> 00:19:35,272
I can imagine the Buddha smiling quietly at that.

137
00:19:36,733 --> 00:19:39,478
The path is now cleared for his Parinibbana.

138
00:19:41,804 --> 00:19:44,906
The next step is for the Buddha to relinquish the will to live.

139
00:19:46,608 --> 00:19:57,039
At this point, Mara, the personification of evil in Buddhism, makes his final appearance in the Buddha's life, trying to get the Buddha to make a hasty exit into Parinirvana.

140
00:19:58,721 --> 00:20:10,073
Though the scriptures always personify Mara as an evil being who tempts the Buddha, we can also see this in more mundane terms, as the last vestiges of desire within the Buddha himself.

141
00:20:12,060 --> 00:20:15,047
And this last temptation of the Buddha is for Nibbana.

142
00:20:17,030 --> 00:20:25,307
Those of you who saw Martin Scorsese's film, The Last Temptation of Christ, will know that Scorsese imagines Christ to be tempted by the desire for life.

143
00:20:26,570 --> 00:20:33,444
In the Buddha's case, his last temptation was not for life, but for the escape from the round of life and death.

144
00:20:35,230 --> 00:20:42,499
Having accomplished all that was expected of a Buddha, Mara tempts him to bask in the perfect contentment and peace of Nibbana.

145
00:20:44,561 --> 00:20:54,854
But to succumb to this final desire would be to grasp at Nibbana, to see it as mine, a state that could be contained within the Buddha's humanity.

146
00:20:56,497 --> 00:20:59,279
Needless to say, the Buddha doesn't fall for this.

147
00:21:00,239 --> 00:21:11,296
Normally he vanquishes Mara vigorously, first and foremost by detecting the presence of Mara and then by expounding the Dhamma to show how Mara's temptations are no match for the Buddha's wisdom.

148
00:21:12,537 --> 00:21:14,901
The vanquished Mara slinks off in misery.

149
00:21:15,903 --> 00:21:28,221
For example, in one description, Mara is left silent, dismayed, with shoulders drooping and head down, glum, with nothing to say, scraping the ground with a reed.

150
00:21:30,849 --> 00:21:38,000
Curiously, in this last bout between the pair, the Buddha is uncharacteristically accommodating.

151
00:21:39,282 --> 00:21:42,669
He simply says, You need not worry, evil one.

152
00:21:43,490 --> 00:21:46,213
The Buddha's passing will not be long delayed.

153
00:21:48,538 --> 00:21:53,144
We can take this as a suggestion for how we might deal with our own desires for enlightenment.

154
00:21:54,391 --> 00:21:58,655
We don't have to quash these out of hand as we might a desire for sense pleasure.

155
00:21:59,758 --> 00:22:06,385
We can take a gentler approach, recognising the worthy aim of the desire, while refusing the temptation to grasp.

156
00:22:08,328 --> 00:22:09,891
Let's take a practical example.

157
00:22:12,153 --> 00:22:15,538
Striving for insight is an experience we probably all go through.

158
00:22:16,615 --> 00:22:25,490
Let's see how a modified version of the Buddha's response might help, repeating to ourselves, Do not worry, evil one, insight will come in its own time.

159
00:22:28,134 --> 00:22:35,807
I tried this out one time when I felt myself straining to get on top of things, trying to see how I was causing so much dukkha for myself.

160
00:22:37,490 --> 00:22:42,318
Repeating the phrase helped me see my experience from a more objective point of view.

161
00:22:43,902 --> 00:22:53,810
Grasping at insight was experienced as physical tension manifesting at several points of my body, the diaphragm, the chest, throat and face.

162
00:22:55,833 --> 00:23:06,666
It was almost as if there was a gigantic hand stretching upwards inside my body clutching at a stream of very unpleasant sensations that were shooting upwards towards my head.

163
00:23:07,628 --> 00:23:13,916
It seemed so imperative that I catch these sensations holding one of them long enough to get a good look at it.

164
00:23:13,936 --> 00:23:20,766
After a few moments the phrase evil one gave me pause for thought.

165
00:23:22,367 --> 00:23:24,590
Why was this grasping really evil?

166
00:23:25,751 --> 00:23:28,654
fear and aversion surfaced as I considered this.

167
00:23:30,056 --> 00:23:35,883
To my surprise the grasping diminished somewhat as if cowed by the judgment evil.

168
00:23:37,144 --> 00:23:45,593
By now I could see the link between this exercise and one of the steps in the Sutta we considered a few nights ago on the removal of distracting thoughts.

169
00:23:46,673 --> 00:23:54,662
You may remember the step where we condemn ourselves harshly for the distraction even imagining a carcass being slung around our necks.

170
00:23:56,042 --> 00:24:05,813
The phrase evil one was having a similar effect, quelling the unskilful desire, holding it in check so it could be examined objectively.

171
00:24:08,236 --> 00:24:16,845
By comparison, the phrase do not worry had a soothing effect and helped me consider the concept evil one in a more balanced way.

172
00:24:18,326 --> 00:24:24,952
I could sense the judgment as valid, seeing the dukkha I was creating by grasping and how unskilful this was.

173
00:24:26,501 --> 00:24:29,326
However, it wasn't a total self-condemnation.

174
00:24:30,449 --> 00:24:33,013
The grasping was just one portion of my experience.

175
00:24:34,015 --> 00:24:41,087
The effort to say the phrase, do not worry, was separate from the grasping and was sensed as caring and wise.

176
00:24:42,951 --> 00:24:50,163
Thus the phrase, do not worry, evil one, had the effect of showing me the dukkha being caused by grasping.

177
00:24:51,510 --> 00:24:59,662
Although the concept evil one stirred fear and judgment, this was being used to avail, clarifying where my problem lay.

178
00:24:59,682 --> 00:25:11,577
The second half of the reflection, insight will come in its own time, helped me to step back and get a wider view of my experience.

179
00:25:12,637 --> 00:25:16,988
I noticed a mental image of light which appeared to be glowing gently above my head.

180
00:25:18,109 --> 00:25:22,219
This I sensed represented the insight I was grasping after.

181
00:25:22,239 --> 00:25:27,631
I felt the sadness of being unable to make direct contact with that gentle light.

182
00:25:28,854 --> 00:25:30,376
It seemed always out of reach.

183
00:25:31,555 --> 00:25:37,502
But some comfort trickled through as I repeated the phrase, Insight will come in its own time.

184
00:25:38,743 --> 00:25:41,647
The comfort seemed to emanate from the light itself.

185
00:25:42,689 --> 00:25:51,099
Once I stopped grasping after it, the light became a compassionate warm glow, softening the stinging sensations of grief.

186
00:25:51,400 --> 00:25:56,446
As the meditation evolved, I found myself making peace with my current level of understanding.

187
00:25:57,828 --> 00:26:08,364
I felt deeply grateful for every scrap of it, every moment where I stopped grasping and let my imperfect wisdom soothe me, reassure me that I was on the right path.

188
00:26:12,148 --> 00:26:21,221
It might also be useful to try out this exercise if you sense any grief at the closing of the retreat or any dread of going back into the big bad world.

189
00:26:22,923 --> 00:26:31,872
This grief or dread represents a tendency to grasp whatever peace, clarity, metta or other form of goodness you touched upon during the retreat.

190
00:26:33,875 --> 00:26:38,960
There is wisdom in the desire for these qualities, so you don't want to condemn the desire itself.

191
00:26:40,441 --> 00:26:50,432
Wise desire is termed chanda in Pali, to distinguish it from the unwise desire for sense pleasures, fame, success and so on.

192
00:26:51,576 --> 00:26:57,904
Those unskillful desires are termed tanha, and these are the ones that lead to suffering.

193
00:26:57,924 --> 00:27:01,548
Chanda, on the other hand, energises our path to freedom.

194
00:27:04,573 --> 00:27:08,356
And yet, grasping after beautiful states of mind brings suffering.

195
00:27:10,058 --> 00:27:14,365
Clarity and metta and all such states come and go depending on conditions.

196
00:27:15,987 --> 00:27:20,352
So you might like to experiment with the phrase, Do not worry, evil one.

197
00:27:20,702 --> 00:27:28,051
there will be another retreat next year and see whether that helps you face into the world outside of Satipaña.

198
00:27:31,756 --> 00:27:37,083
But always remember that Vipassana is your primary tool in dealing with any emotional disturbance.

199
00:27:37,943 --> 00:27:42,108
This is just a suggestion that might help you tweak yourself in the right direction.

200
00:27:43,089 --> 00:27:49,156
It's a form of self-care, finding the appropriate reflection to help you through a challenging situation.

201
00:27:51,854 --> 00:28:02,259
Back to the Buddha's last days now, where having soothed Mara in this final exchange between them, he is then able to renounce his will to live in a perfectly equanimous way.

202
00:28:02,319 --> 00:28:09,356
He then announces to Ananda and the other disciples that he will pass away in three months' time.

203
00:28:11,615 --> 00:28:27,384
All of this part of the story, the rain's retreat, his sickness, his comments on beauty, his offer to live to a century, his last exchange with Mara and his renunciation of the will to live, happened in Vasali.

204
00:28:29,428 --> 00:28:34,837
We are told that as he leaves the region, he gazed on it with an elephant's look.

205
00:28:35,881 --> 00:28:43,112
meaning that he turned his full body around to look behind him, just as an elephant has to do if he wants to look behind.

206
00:28:44,913 --> 00:28:52,164
After this long gaze, he tells Ananda that this is the last time he will see Vasali.

207
00:28:53,467 --> 00:29:02,901
The Buddha wasn't one for idle chatter, so we can assume this comment and his elephant's look were poignant expressions of appreciation and farewell.

208
00:29:04,146 --> 00:29:10,457
So many of the Buddha's teachings hammer home the need not to attach ourselves to anything in the phenomenal world.

209
00:29:11,357 --> 00:29:15,765
But that's not to say we distance ourselves from the world, disdaining what it offers.

210
00:29:17,027 --> 00:29:25,460
Enlightenment hasn't removed the Buddha from the earth, neither in terms of the aches and pains of old age, nor the beauty he finds in Vasali.

211
00:29:26,561 --> 00:29:29,866
His Buddha nature participates fully in his humanity.

212
00:29:33,339 --> 00:29:38,979
This reflection provides another encouragement not to neglect mundane reality in our search for enlightenment.

213
00:29:40,002 --> 00:29:41,627
We engage fully in the world.

214
00:29:42,391 --> 00:29:44,498
It's where we find our path to freedom.

215
00:29:46,115 --> 00:29:51,741
We can afford to get fond of whatever places or people or aspects of the world that enrich our lives.

216
00:29:52,962 --> 00:30:00,632
The only thing we have to keep reminding ourselves is that all delight depends on a multitude of conditions beyond our control.

217
00:30:00,672 --> 00:30:03,895
It will all fall apart someday.

218
00:30:05,798 --> 00:30:13,606
We have to find the courage to appreciate and enjoy and love all the wholesome but ephemeral pleasures of the world.

219
00:30:16,607 --> 00:30:21,375
Saying farewell is perhaps the most challenging aspect of appreciation.

220
00:30:22,857 --> 00:30:33,714
The Buddha's elephant look towards Vasali gives us a clear indication not to fudge on this, so intent on our next move that we ignore what we're leaving behind.

221
00:30:35,076 --> 00:30:38,682
Saying goodbye is a poignant mudita practice.

222
00:30:41,380 --> 00:30:49,191
Having said his farewell to Vasali, the Buddha spends the next three months travelling from place to place in the manner he had done since he started teaching.

223
00:30:50,051 --> 00:30:53,156
In Pava, he eats a meal which gives him food poisoning.

224
00:30:53,998 --> 00:31:01,028
Next day, obviously very ill, he succeeds in making his way to Kusinara, where he will die.

225
00:31:01,087 --> 00:31:10,981
Next time you're suffering the indignity of vomiting and diarrhoea, you might comfort yourself with the thought that this was how the Buddha died, so you're in good company.

226
00:31:12,936 --> 00:31:22,665
The Sutta suggests that Kusanara was a quiet rural region and Ananda remonstrates with the Buddha for choosing such a miserable little backwater of a place in which to die.

227
00:31:22,726 --> 00:31:29,913
He urges him to go to one of the great cities instead, declaring that would be a more fitting place for the Buddha to die.

228
00:31:31,375 --> 00:31:39,061
Although Ananda grieved sorely at the Buddha's passing, his understanding of the Dhamma told him that Parinibbana was something to celebrate.

229
00:31:40,509 --> 00:31:48,558
This sentiment was captured in one of the verses written after the Buddha's death and which we chant every morning as part of the Vipassana verses.

230
00:31:50,780 --> 00:31:52,682
All conditioned things are impermanent.

231
00:31:53,644 --> 00:31:55,905
It is their nature to arise and pass away.

232
00:31:56,686 --> 00:31:58,429
Having arisen, they disappear.

233
00:31:59,349 --> 00:32:01,352
Their cessation is happiness.

234
00:32:03,534 --> 00:32:05,936
Wouldn't it be wonderful to live from such wisdom?

235
00:32:07,018 --> 00:32:09,740
To know that death is the deepest happiness.

236
00:32:10,800 --> 00:32:23,217
We could give ourselves fully into every activity, every relationship, enjoy all wholesome aspects of life to the full knowing that the truest bliss will come when all this activity fades away.

237
00:32:25,078 --> 00:32:27,662
It really is to get the best of both worlds.

238
00:32:30,465 --> 00:32:32,709
Ananda, however, was not fully enlightened.

239
00:32:33,769 --> 00:32:36,993
The verse he uttered on the Buddha's passing confessed his suffering.

240
00:32:38,324 --> 00:32:44,737
Terrible was the quaking, men's hair stood on end, when the all-accomplished Buddha passed away.

241
00:32:47,502 --> 00:32:56,923
Before we come to that best of both worlds wisdom, we bear witness to the dukkha that results from attaching ourselves to anything in this world of phenomena.

242
00:32:59,906 --> 00:33:11,239
Perhaps to symbolise this, the Buddha rejects Ananda's wish for him to celebrate Parinirvana in the style of earthly splendour, in a big city surrounded by pomp and circumstance.

243
00:33:12,340 --> 00:33:22,211
Likewise, he turns his back on the more refined beauties of the world, symbolised by the shrines of Asali and other centres where he had lived, established monasteries and taught.

244
00:33:23,452 --> 00:33:28,057
He chooses instead the relative obscurity of Kusinara for his final release.

245
00:33:29,404 --> 00:33:40,596
Perhaps this was to symbolise that the path leads forever onwards, beyond what is already established, into the unknown, into silence, the quiet peace of Nibbana.

246
00:33:45,141 --> 00:33:54,130
At one point during this last day of the Buddha's life, Ananda can no longer contain his grief and withdraws to a quiet spot to weep.

247
00:33:55,797 --> 00:34:05,351
When the Buddha hears of this he summons him, telling him not to grieve, reminding him that all earthly phenomena, no matter how dear, must pass away.

248
00:34:05,391 --> 00:34:13,101
This is tough love, but his next comments show a deep sensitivity toward the grieving process.

249
00:34:14,563 --> 00:34:16,827
He praises Ananda for his services.

250
00:34:17,802 --> 00:34:32,088
For a long time, Ananda, you have been in the Buddha's presence, showing loving kindness in acts of body, speech and mind, beneficially, blessedly, wholeheartedly and unstintingly.

251
00:34:33,751 --> 00:34:36,215
He commends the way Ananda has administered his work.

252
00:34:37,630 --> 00:34:40,052
Monks, Ananda is wise.

253
00:34:40,853 --> 00:34:49,742
He knows when it is the right time for monks to come and see the Buddha, when it's the right time for nuns, for lay people, for kings, and so on.

254
00:34:51,304 --> 00:35:01,056
He then lauds Ananda's many endearing qualities, telling how people are always pleased to see him, delighted when he speaks to them, disappointed if he is silent.

255
00:35:03,836 --> 00:35:09,003
When we grieve someone's passing we unwittingly diminish our own value.

256
00:35:10,384 --> 00:35:18,673
Psychologically we let our strength and happiness die with them, projecting all our good qualities onto the dying person.

257
00:35:20,655 --> 00:35:25,862
Working our way through grief is to recover our confidence, our self-worth.

258
00:35:27,614 --> 00:35:34,507
The Buddha hastens Ananda's recovery in this public expression of appreciation, praise and admiration for his friend.

259
00:35:35,971 --> 00:35:41,121
In this parting kindness to Ananda, the Buddha leaves us with the conundrum of Anatta.

260
00:35:42,364 --> 00:35:46,972
We need to cherish ourselves in order to see through the delusion of self.

261
00:35:51,255 --> 00:35:57,864
Before we let the Buddha take his final breath, let's look back at some of the points we can take from this discourse.

262
00:35:59,326 --> 00:36:04,112
Firstly, it gives us a picture of the Buddha as a very real human being.

263
00:36:05,853 --> 00:36:08,476
His enlightened state is fully incarnate in the world.

264
00:36:09,639 --> 00:36:14,664
It does not shield him from aches and pains or from unexpected and untimely illness.

265
00:36:15,893 --> 00:36:20,362
Neither does it leave him immune to the beauty of the world or the joy of friendship.

266
00:36:21,505 --> 00:36:24,711
These are needed to fuel his energy and will to live.

267
00:36:26,896 --> 00:36:31,827
See if you can find occasions for mudita during these last days of the retreat.

268
00:36:33,291 --> 00:36:52,916
If there are any aspects of Satipaña which helped you along, the shrine or walking rooms, some restful spot in the meadows, your favourite walking path, the stupa or any of the statues that meant something to you, spend a few moments acknowledging these, expressing gratitude for whatever way they inspired you.

269
00:36:54,257 --> 00:36:59,063
When leaving, turn back, elephant style, to say farewell.

270
00:37:02,806 --> 00:37:08,438
We can also remember the Buddha's last days as a contemplation on sickness, ageing and death.

271
00:37:10,161 --> 00:37:18,519
Within our imagination we might be all powerful but these provide objective limitations on what we can achieve in the world.

272
00:37:20,204 --> 00:37:27,193
The really good news is that provided we give things our best shot we can take these limitations as a gift.

273
00:37:28,414 --> 00:37:35,063
We can bow out delighted that the struggle is over and that we can now relax and let go.

274
00:37:35,085 --> 00:37:42,594
The Sutta shows the important role Ananda played in the Buddha's life.

275
00:37:43,876 --> 00:37:48,523
Much of what we know about the Buddha comes from the long conversations he has with Ananda.

276
00:37:49,599 --> 00:37:55,628
He tells him what is on his mind, uses him as a sounding board and comforts him in his grief.

277
00:37:57,411 --> 00:38:00,474
We can let ourselves be inspired by their relationship.

278
00:38:01,675 --> 00:38:08,945
Over these last days you might spend time thinking of your friends, especially those with whom you share the spiritual path.

279
00:38:10,108 --> 00:38:15,355
You could vow to develop these friendships and share the merits of your retreat with them.

280
00:38:18,135 --> 00:38:30,934
Despite all the evidence of the Buddha's love for and appreciation of the people and places that played a role in his life, his last temptation was not for life, but for the peace and bliss of Nibbana.

281
00:38:32,396 --> 00:38:41,307
Remembering this, we incline our minds to that ultimate bliss and encourage ourselves to find happiness in letting go.

282
00:38:43,903 --> 00:38:48,791
But the Buddha didn't give in to Mara's last temptation for him to bow out early.

283
00:38:49,992 --> 00:39:00,309
He maintained his mission to teach the Dhamma right up to the end, answering questions, advising people on specific points, giving Dhamma talks.

284
00:39:00,329 --> 00:39:06,679
It is said at the very last moments of his life, his disciples all fell silent.

285
00:39:06,699 --> 00:39:12,206
Three times he asked if there were any more questions, but no one voiced any.

286
00:39:14,632 --> 00:39:17,800
With that, the Buddha uttered his last words.

287
00:39:20,905 --> 00:39:24,333
All compound things have the nature to decay.

288
00:39:24,373 --> 00:39:28,882
Strive diligently for your liberation.

289
00:39:31,367 --> 00:39:34,514
With that, the Buddha took his last breath.

290
00:39:36,097 --> 00:39:44,775
His enlightened state was no longer incarnate within the five aggregates of body and mind through which he had lived his life and been known by others.

291
00:39:46,557 --> 00:39:51,728
The Sutta goes on to describe the ceremonies that followed and the division of the relics of his body.

292
00:39:53,271 --> 00:39:57,820
But I think the Buddha's last breath is the best point at which to take our leave.

293
00:40:00,786 --> 00:40:07,594
As we contemplate his Parinibbana, we may, in part, feel the anxiety and sorrow of Ananda.

294
00:40:09,014 --> 00:40:19,045
Another part of us might rejoice in the wisdom of the Vipassana verse, which declares that true happiness comes when all things pass away.

295
00:40:21,608 --> 00:40:26,472
Torn between these extremes, we might feel stuck and confused.

296
00:40:28,224 --> 00:40:35,721
All of this, our wisdom and our many layers of delusion, is witnessed by the untraceable.

